definition.value: A protein containing more than one iron and acid-labile sulfur, that displays electron-transfer activity but not classical enzyme function.
The 5beta-stereoisomer of 3-hydroxypregnan-20-one.
A retinoid that consists of 3,7-dimethylnona-2,4,6,8-tetraenoic acid having a 4-methoxy-2,3,6-trimethylphenyl group attached at position 9.

A drug that softens, separates, and causes desquamation of the cornified epithelium or horny layer of skin. Keratolytic drugs are used to expose mycelia of infecting fungi or to treat corns, warts, and certain other skin diseases.
A drug used to treat or prevent skin disorders or for the routine care of skin.
A hydroxyisoflavanone that is isoflavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7 and 2' and a methoxy group at position 4' respectively.
A class of synthetic expanded porphyrins with a 22 pi-electron aromatic system. They are named after the state of Texas where these compounds were first synthesised.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the activity of cytochrome P450 involved in catalysis of organic substances.
A compound which inhibits the movement of an ion across an energy-transducing cell membrane.
Any pathway inhibitor that inhibits the synthesis of fatty acids.
A substance that can be converted into a vitamin by animal tissues.
An azabicycloalkane that is the 10,11-dihydro-5H-dibenzo[a,d]cyclohepten-5-yl ether of tropine.
A member of the class of ferrichromes that is an iron(III) chelate of a homodetic cyclic peptide made up of a tripeptide of glycine and a tripeptide of N(4)-acetyl-N(4)-hydroxy-L-ornithine.
A citrate salt that is the dihydrogen citrate salt of deptropamine.
An imine formed formally from a quinone by replacement of one or more atoms of quinonoid oxygen by =NH or =NR.
Any member of the class of benzaldehydes in which the phenyl ring is substituted by two hydroxy groups.
A dihydroxybenzaldehyde that is resorcinol which has been substituted by a formyl group para to one of the hydroxy groups.
A quinolone that is 4-oxo-1,4-dihydroquinoline which is substituted at positions 1, 3, 6 and 7 by ethyl, carboxy, fluorine, and 4-methylpiperazin-1-yl groups, respectively.
The (R)-enantiomer of naringenin.
A trihydroxyflavanone that is flavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 6 and 4'.
A trihydroxyflavanone that is (S)-naringenin having a prenyl group at position 8.
A tetrahydroxyflavanone having the hydroxy groups at the 2'-, 4'-, 5- and 7-positions and a prenyl group at 8-position.

A tetrahydroxyflavanone having a structure of naringenin bearing an additional hydroxyl substituent at position 2' as well as a (2R)-5-methyl-2-(prop-1-en-2-yl)hex-4-en-1-yl (lavandulyl) substituent at position 8'.
A retinoid consisting of 3,7-dimethylnona-2,4,6,8-tetraen-1-ol substituted at position 9 by a 2,6,6-trimethylcyclohex-1-en-1-yl group (geometry of the four exocyclic double bonds is not specified).

A benzocycloheptathiophene that is 9,10-dihydro-4H-benzo[4,5]cyclohepta[1,2-b]thiophene 4-ylidene)-1-methylpiperidine which is joined from the 4 position to the 4 position of an N-methylpiperidine moiety by a double bond. It is a sedating antihistamine, with strong serotonin antagonist and weak antimuscarinic activity. It is generally used as the malate salt for the treatment of migraine and the prevention of headache attacks during cluster periods.

A malate salt resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of pizotifen and malic acid. A sedating antihistamine with strong serotonin antagonist and weak antimuscarinic activity, it is used for the treatment of migraine and the prevention of headache attacks during cluster periods.
A maleate salt obtained by reaction of pizotifen with one equivalent of maleic acid.
A p-menthane monoterpenoid that is the dihydro derivative of  carveol.
An EC 3.1.* (ester hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of a phosphoric diester hydrolase (EC 3.1.4.*).
benzocycloheptathiophenes
